Here, for your reference, are the various entities that have decided to operate the PC-21, along with those contemplating its acquisition.

### Current operators

*   [Australia](/Australia) (49)
    *   [Royal Australian Air Force](/Royal_Australian_Air_Force): 49 aircraft were ordered in September 2015, with deliveries successfully concluded by November 2019 [49] [50].
*   [France](/France) (17 + 9)
    *   [French Air and Space Force](/French_Air_and_Space_Force) (Armée de l'air et de l'espace): An initial order for 17 units was placed in January 2017 [51], with all delivered by August 2019. A subsequent order for an additional 9 aircraft was made in 2021, slated for delivery in 2023 [52] [53] [54].
*   [Jordan](/Jordan) (12)
    *   [Royal Jordanian Air Force](/Royal_Jordanian_Air_Force): A total of 12 aircraft have been delivered as of August 2019. This comprises 8 initially ordered in 2015 (replacing a previous order for 9 [PC-9Ms](/Pilatus_PC-9)), with 2 additional options converted in October 2016, and a further 2 ordered in January 2017 [54] [55].
*   [Qatar](/Qatar) (24)
    *   [Qatar Emiri Air Force](/Qatar_Emiri_Air_Force): 24 aircraft were ordered in July 2012, with the first deliveries commencing in 2014 [56].
*   [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia) (55)
    *   [Royal Saudi Air Force](/Royal_Saudi_Air_Force): 55 aircraft were ordered in May 2012, with initial deliveries starting in 2014 [31].
*   [Singapore](/Singapore) (19)
    *   [Republic of Singapore Air Force](/Republic_of_Singapore_Air_Force): As the launch export customer, [Singapore](/Singapore) operates 19 PC-21s in [Australia](/Australia) for its Basic Wings Course (BWC). This is part of a comprehensive availability contract involving Lockheed Martin and Hawker Pacific, a rather complex arrangement [35].
*   [Spain](/Spain) (40)
    *   [Spanish Air and Space Force](/Spanish_Air_and_Space_Force): A total of 40 aircraft have been acquired across two distinct batches.
        *   Orders:
            *   24 aircraft were ordered in January 2020 [57]. The deliveries for this first batch unfolded as follows:
                *   The first two PC-21s were delivered in September 2021 [58].
                *   The final aircraft from this batch arrived in mid-2022 [59].
            *   An additional 16 aircraft were ordered in March 2023 [60]. Deliveries for this second batch are scheduled:
                *   The first is expected in June 2024 [61].
                *   The last is anticipated in November 2025 [62].
*   [Switzerland](/Switzerland) (8)
    *   [Swiss Air Force](/Swiss_Air_Force): Operates 8 PC-21s for advanced training, having replaced the [BAe Hawk](/BAE_Systems_Hawk) fleet which was retired in 2003.
*   [United Arab Emirates](/United_Arab_Emirates) (25)
    *   [United Arab Emirates Air Force](/United_Arab_Emirates_Air_Force): Operates 25 aircraft for advanced training. The first flight for the UAEAF fleet occurred on 22 November 2010. This was part of a deal valued at CHF 520 million [54].
*   [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) (2)
    *   [Qinetiq](/Qinetiq): Operates two PC-21s for advanced training on behalf of the rather prestigious [Empire Test Pilot School](/Empire_Test_Pilot_School) at Boscombe Down [63]. One assumes they know what they're doing.

### Future operators

*   [Canada](/Canada) (19)
    *   SkyAlyne has been selected to train future [Canadian Air Force](/Canadian_Armed_Forces) pilots through the Future Aircrew Training (FAcT) program, in collaboration with CAE and KF Aerospace. Pilots will undergo training on a variety of platforms, including the [Grob 120TP](/Grob_G_120TP) (CT-102B Astra II), the PC-21 (CT-157 Siskin II), the [King Air 260](/Beechcraft_Super_King_Air) (CT-145E Expeditor II), the [H135](/H135) (CT-153 Juno), and the [Dash 8-400](/De_Havilland_Canada_Dash_8) (CT-142Q Citadel), depending on their assigned specialization [64] [65]. The acquisition of the 19 PC-21 aircraft was formally confirmed in November 2024 [66].

### Potential customers

*   [Bulgaria](/Bulgaria)
    *   [Bulgarian Air Force](/Bulgarian_Air_Force): The [Bulgarian Ministry of Defence](/Ministry_of_Defence_(Bulgaria)) is reportedly in discussions with [Pilatus Aircraft](/Pilatus_Aircraft) regarding the acquisition of PC-21s. These aircraft would serve as replacements for their existing [PC-9Ms](/Pilatus_PC-9) (and potentially their aging [L-39s](/Aero_L-39_Albatros)) as part of a broader modernization initiative tied to the [F-16 Block 70](/F-16) procurement project [67].
*   [Malaysia](/Malaysia)
    *   [Royal Malaysian Air Force](/Royal_Malaysian_Air_Force) [68].
*   [Sweden](/Sweden)
    *   [Swedish Air Force](/Swedish_Air_Force): Requires a successor for its long-serving [Saab 105](/Saab_105) fleet [69] [70]. While the [T-7 Red Hawk](/Boeing%E2%80%93Saab_T-7_Red_Hawk), partially designed and manufactured by [Saab](/Saab_AB), is considered a strong contender, the more favorable price point of the PC-21 presents a significant advantage in this competitive landscape. Cost, it seems, still matters [70].
*   [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom)
    *   [Pilatus](/Pilatus_Aircraft) has joined the tender process for the replacement of the [BAE Hawk](/BAE_Systems_Hawk) fleet operated by the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) [71]. A challenging proposition, given the Hawk's iconic status.

